chordpro:
{title: I Heard the Bells on Christmas Day}
{subtitle: Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, 1863 / John Baptiste Calkin tune "Waltham", 1872}
{key: F}
{time: 4/4}
{tempo: 80}
{comment: Written during the American Civil War. The closing verses turn from despair to hope: "God is not dead, nor doth He sleep."}

{start_of_verse: 1}
[F]I heard the [Bb]bells on [F]Christmas [C]Day
[F]Their old, fa[Bb]miliar [C]carols [F]play
[Dm]And wild and [Am]sweet [Bb]the words re[C]peat
[F]Of peace on [Bb]earth, good-[C]will to [F]men!
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 2}
[F]And thought how, [Bb]as the [F]day had [C]come
[F]The belfries [Bb]of all [C]Christen[F]dom
[Dm]Had rolled a[Am]long [Bb]the unbroken [C]song
[F]Of peace on [Bb]earth, good-[C]will to [F]men!
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 3}
[F]Till ringing, [Bb]singing [F]on its [C]way
[F]The world re[Bb]volved from [C]night to [F]day
[Dm]A voice, a [Am]chime, [Bb]a chant sub[C]lime
[F]Of peace on [Bb]earth, good-[C]will to [F]men!
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 4}
[F]Then from each [Bb]black, ac[F]cursed [C]mouth
[F]The cannon [Bb]thundered [C]in the [F]South
[Dm]And with the [Am]sound [Bb]the carols [C]drowned
[F]Of peace on [Bb]earth, good-[C]will to [F]men!
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 5}
[F]It was as if [Bb]an earth[F]quake [C]rent
[F]The hearth-[Bb]stones of a [C]conti[F]nent
[Dm]And made for[Am]lorn [Bb]the households [C]born
[F]Of peace on [Bb]earth, good-[C]will to [F]men!
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 6}
[F]And in des[Bb]pair I [F]bowed my [C]head
[F]"There is no [Bb]peace on [C]earth," I [F]said
[Dm]"For hate is [Am]strong, [Bb]and mocks the [C]song
[F]Of peace on [Bb]earth, good-[C]will to [F]men!"
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 7}
[F]Then pealed the [Bb]bells more [F]loud and [C]deep:
[F]"God is not [Bb]dead, nor [C]doth He [F]sleep
[Dm]The Wrong shall [Am]fail, [Bb]the Right pre[C]vail
[F]With peace on [Bb]earth, good-[C]will to [F]men."
{end_of_verse}
